00:32:43.890 --> 00:32:46.900
But then again, this repeated theme of

00:32:46.900 --> 00:32:49.430
the chemistry doesn't
always neatly line up,

00:32:49.430 --> 00:32:54.360
because mescaline looks more like dopamine

00:32:54.360 --> 00:32:55.820
than it does like serotonin,

00:32:55.820 --> 00:32:59.020
but yet, at the receptor activation level,

00:32:59.020 --> 00:33:03.210
the pharmalogical effect,
those are similar.

00:33:03.210 --> 00:33:07.780
But yeah, I mean, and what it
does at the receptor is an...

00:33:07.780 --> 00:33:09.040
It's hitting the same switch,

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:11.950
but then having an alternate response

00:33:11.950 --> 00:33:14.313
at the receptor level.
- Yeah, so for people

00:33:14.313 --> 00:33:15.710
that don't necessarily understand

00:33:15.710 --> 00:33:17.700
the relationship between
what we call ligand,

00:33:17.700 --> 00:33:19.440
the thing that parks in the receptor,

00:33:19.440 --> 00:33:21.280
and the receptor is the parking spot,

00:33:21.280 --> 00:33:22.960
one of the reasons that you can get

00:33:22.960 --> 00:33:26.880
such a variety of effects
from different compounds is,

00:33:26.880 --> 00:33:30.520
for instance, serotonin might
affect a certain pathway

00:33:30.520 --> 00:33:32.130
at a particular rate,

00:33:32.130 --> 00:33:35.510
and a psilocybin might trigger activation

00:33:35.510 --> 00:33:37.610
of different components of
that pathway, different rates,

00:33:37.610 --> 00:33:40.340
and so you can get vastly
different experiences

00:33:40.340 --> 00:33:42.598
from two things that
look chemically similar.

00:33:42.598 --> 00:33:43.431
- Right.
- This is also

00:33:43.431 --> 00:33:47.840
a good reason why people
shouldn't just assume

00:33:47.840 --> 00:33:50.850
that they can cowboy their
