00:53:52.027 --> 00:53:53.960
and anxiety because of their cancer,

00:53:53.960 --> 00:53:55.060
and also our work with people

00:53:55.060 --> 00:53:57.570
trying to quit cigarette smoking.

00:53:57.570 --> 00:54:00.810
I mean, there's this real...

00:54:00.810 --> 00:54:02.570
There seems to be, when it really works,

00:54:02.570 --> 00:54:06.400
this change in how people view themselves,

00:54:06.400 --> 00:54:07.320
like with smoking,

00:54:07.320 --> 00:54:12.320
like really stepping out
of this model of like,

00:54:12.410 --> 00:54:15.670
I'm a smoker, it's tough
to quit smoking cigarettes.

00:54:15.670 --> 00:54:16.680
I can't do it.

00:54:16.680 --> 00:54:18.450
I failed a bunch of times.

00:54:18.450 --> 00:54:20.830
I remember one participant
during the session,

00:54:20.830 --> 00:54:22.867
but he held onto this afterward, said,

00:54:22.867 --> 00:54:26.830
"My god, it's like I
can really just decide,

00:54:26.830 --> 00:54:27.720
like flicking off a button,

00:54:27.720 --> 00:54:29.730
I can decide not to smoke".

00:54:29.730 --> 00:54:32.037
I call these duh experiences
with psychedelics,

00:54:32.037 --> 00:54:35.867
'cause people often, like in
the cancer stage, you say,

00:54:35.867 --> 00:54:38.027
"I'm causing most of my own suffering".

00:54:38.998 --> 00:54:40.250
I can follow my appointments.

00:54:40.250 --> 00:54:41.083
I can do everything,

00:54:41.083 --> 00:54:42.050
but I can still plan for the...

00:54:42.050 --> 00:54:44.910
I'm not getting outside in the sunshine.

00:54:44.910 --> 00:54:46.460
I'm not playing with my grandkids.

00:54:46.460 --> 00:54:47.730
I'm choosing to do that.

00:54:47.730 --> 00:54:49.877
And it's like, they told
themselves that before,

00:54:49.877 --> 00:54:53.740
and the smoker has told themselves
a million times, I can...

00:54:53.740 --> 00:54:54.573
So it sounds...

00:54:54.573 --> 00:54:56.370
When it comes out of their mouths,

00:54:56.370 --> 00:54:57.203
folks will say,

00:54:57.203 --> 00:54:58.350
this is part of the ineffability

00:54:58.350 --> 00:54:59.450
of a psychedelic experience,

00:54:59.450 --> 00:55:01.460
folks say, "I know this
sounds like bullshit

00:55:01.460 --> 00:55:02.380
and this sounds like,

00:55:02.380 --> 00:55:05.440
but my god, I could just sigh",

00:55:05.440 --> 00:55:09.040
like they're feeling
this gravity of agency,

00:55:09.040 --> 00:55:10.150
which I think is interesting,

00:55:10.150 --> 00:55:15.150
cause regardless of the debates
on the reality of freewill,

00:55:15.700 --> 00:55:18.350
I think the philosophy of that,

00:55:18.350 --> 00:55:20.880
whether it's ultimately free will,

00:55:20.880 --> 00:55:23.010
like pure agency, if that exists,

00:55:23.010 --> 00:55:24.360
which I'm skeptical of,

00:55:24.360 --> 00:55:28.630
or just the idea, that clearly,
we have a sense of agency.

00:55:28.630 --> 00:55:30.400
There's something there,

00:55:30.400 --> 00:55:32.493
whether it's the sense of agency even,

00:55:34.040 --> 00:55:35.570
the human being has,

00:55:35.570 --> 00:55:38.910
and that seems to be, at times,

00:55:38.910 --> 00:55:43.240
fundamentally, supercharged
from a psychedelic experience.

00:55:43.240 --> 00:55:46.790
This idea like, I'm just
going to make a decision.

00:55:46.790 --> 00:55:48.800
Like normally, like you
tell a depressed person,

00:55:48.800 --> 00:55:50.350
don't think of yourself that way.

00:55:50.350 --> 00:55:51.183
You're not a failure.

00:55:51.183 --> 00:55:52.016
- They can't do it.
[interposing voices]

00:55:52.016 --> 00:55:52.849
- It's just, yeah.

00:55:52.849 --> 00:55:53.682
It's like-
- Right.

00:55:53.682 --> 00:55:54.550
- Well-
- But you can, actually,

00:55:54.550 --> 00:55:55.730
in one of these states,

00:55:55.730 --> 00:55:57.920
have an experience where
you realize, like, my god.

00:55:57.920 --> 00:56:00.452
Just like using MDMA to treat PTSD,

00:56:00.452 --> 00:56:01.360
and we're going to be starting work

00:56:01.360 --> 00:56:03.140
with psilocybin to treat PTSD,

00:56:03.140 --> 00:56:06.780
someone could really
reprocess their trauma

00:56:06.780 --> 00:56:09.840
in a way that has lasting effects.

00:56:09.840 --> 00:56:11.480
And clearly, there's
probably something that...

00:56:11.480 --> 00:56:13.680
You know, reconsolidation
of those memories,

00:56:15.660 --> 00:56:17.080
they are altered,

00:56:17.080 --> 00:56:19.310
very consistent with our understanding

00:56:19.310 --> 00:56:20.400
of the way memory works.

00:56:20.400 --> 00:56:22.780
So the whole idea, people can actually,

00:56:22.780 --> 00:56:26.480
in a few hours, have a
such a profound experience

00:56:26.480 --> 00:56:30.330
that they decide to make these changes

00:56:30.330 --> 00:56:32.650
in who they are, and it sticks,

00:56:32.650 --> 00:56:34.207
there seems to be something like that.

00:56:34.207 --> 00:56:35.520
- And that's profound.

00:56:35.520 --> 00:56:38.720
I mean, I think, a few moments ago,

00:56:38.720 --> 00:56:41.430
I made a some semi-disparaging statements

00:56:41.430 --> 00:56:43.890
about things like the
secret, and affirmations,

00:56:43.890 --> 00:56:46.450
and the reason I do that

00:56:47.370 --> 00:56:49.900
with a nod to the fact that the people

00:56:49.900 --> 00:56:51.490
who are putting those ideas forward

00:56:51.490 --> 00:56:53.120
are well-intentioned people,

00:56:53.120 --> 00:56:58.120
is that the neural networks of
the brain put language last.

00:56:59.700 --> 00:57:01.550
We tell stories, you know?

00:57:01.550 --> 00:57:03.080
And stories are very powerful.

00:57:03.080 --> 00:57:07.700
But I think one of the most cruel aspects

00:57:07.700 --> 00:57:11.930
of the whole self-help
literature in popular psychology

00:57:11.930 --> 00:57:13.920
is this idea, that everything you say,

00:57:13.920 --> 00:57:15.870
your brain and body hear it.

00:57:15.870 --> 00:57:19.440
That's actually a very unkind
or even cruel thing for

00:57:19.440 --> 00:57:22.090
people who are depressed
or anxious to hear,

00:57:22.090 --> 00:57:24.100
because if they hear
that, and believe that,

00:57:24.100 --> 00:57:26.300
and I want to be clear,
I don't think it's true,

00:57:26.300 --> 00:57:30.640
that they think that it's
very hard to control thoughts.

00:57:30.640 --> 00:57:32.550
Is it very hard to control thoughts?

00:57:32.550 --> 00:57:35.280
So if somebody says, "I can't",

00:57:35.280 --> 00:57:36.187
and then somebody says,

00:57:36.187 --> 00:57:37.740
"Well, no, every time you say you can't,

00:57:37.740 --> 00:57:39.550
your brain hears that,
and it reinforces it",

00:57:39.550 --> 00:57:41.803
that's a very treacherous place to live.

00:57:42.810 --> 00:57:45.330
And language is powerful,

00:57:45.330 --> 00:57:49.030
but neural networks, the brain,

00:57:49.030 --> 00:57:51.110
and the networks that
underlie emotionality,

00:57:51.110 --> 00:57:53.170
and perception, and sense of self,

00:57:53.170 --> 00:57:56.050
they don't change in response to language.

00:57:56.050 --> 00:57:58.710
They change in response to experience.

00:57:58.710 --> 00:57:59.543
- [Dr. Matthew] Yeah.

00:57:59.543 --> 00:58:01.742
- And just fundamentally,

00:58:01.742 --> 00:58:02.760
there are some prerequisites.

00:58:02.760 --> 00:58:04.690
You need certain neuromodulators present,

00:58:04.690 --> 00:58:06.480
like serotonin or dopamine.

00:58:06.480 --> 00:58:08.290
You need them to be at sufficient levels.

00:58:08.290 --> 00:58:10.440
You don't need a drug
necessarily to do it.

00:58:11.680 --> 00:58:13.610
You give a kid a kitten or a puppy,

00:58:13.610 --> 00:58:14.860
their first kitten or puppy,

00:58:14.860 --> 00:58:17.780
and the levels of dopamine and serotonin,

00:58:17.780 --> 00:58:18.620
I've never measured them,

00:58:18.620 --> 00:58:19.570
but we can be pretty sure

00:58:19.570 --> 00:58:21.880
that they are higher than baseline,

00:58:21.880 --> 00:58:24.550
and that experience will
reshape them, right?

00:58:24.550 --> 00:58:26.180
- Yeah.
- Likewise with an adult

00:58:26.180 --> 00:58:28.320
in certain circumstances.

00:58:28.320 --> 00:58:31.430
So I think I'm fascinated by this idea,

00:58:31.430 --> 00:58:35.940
that a somatic and a
perceptual experience,

00:58:35.940 --> 00:58:39.210
but a real experience of the
sort that you're describing,

00:58:39.210 --> 00:58:40.400
- Yeah.
- is what allows us

00:58:40.400 --> 00:58:41.950
to reshape our neural circuitry,

00:58:41.950 --> 00:58:43.810
and to feel differently about ourselves.

00:58:43.810 --> 00:58:48.740
And I know there's been
really tremendous success

00:58:48.740 --> 00:58:52.460
in many individuals of
alleviating depression,

00:58:52.460 --> 00:58:55.190
of treating trauma with
these different compounds.

00:58:55.190 --> 00:58:56.830
I wanted to step from

00:58:58.145 --> 00:59:01.640
the experience under the
effects of the psychedelic.

00:59:01.640 --> 00:59:03.340
So the person there with your team,

00:59:03.340 --> 00:59:05.920
they go into this expanded
perceptual bubble.

00:59:05.920 --> 00:59:08.050
If things go well,

00:59:08.050 --> 00:59:10.070
they're able to do that
to a really deep degree.

00:59:10.070 --> 00:59:12.400
Maybe it's the relived trauma?

00:59:12.400 --> 00:59:14.630
Maybe it's the beauty of their ability

00:59:14.630 --> 00:59:16.980
to connect to things in the world?

00:59:16.980 --> 00:59:19.930
And I want to talk about the
transition out of that state,

00:59:19.930 --> 00:59:22.030
and then the export into life,

00:59:22.030 --> 00:59:23.240
because this is really where the

00:59:23.240 --> 00:59:25.090
power of psychedelic seems to be

00:59:25.090 --> 00:59:26.550
in the therapeutic sense,

00:59:26.550 --> 00:59:29.610
is the ability to learn, truly
learn, from that experience,

00:59:29.610 --> 00:59:31.920
so that the learning becomes the default.

00:59:31.920 --> 00:59:33.360
That one doesn't have
to remind themselves,

00:59:33.360 --> 00:59:34.520
oh, I am...

00:59:34.520 --> 00:59:35.990
You know, they don't have
to do an affirmation,

00:59:35.990 --> 00:59:37.057
I am a happy person, I am a...

00:59:37.057 --> 00:59:38.300
You know, I always think of

00:59:38.300 --> 00:59:39.190
Bart Simpson
- Right

00:59:39.190 --> 00:59:40.370
- writing on the chalkboard.
[Dr. Matthew laughs]

00:59:40.370 --> 00:59:41.460
- Yeah.
- It didn't work for him

00:59:41.460 --> 00:59:43.510
It doesn't work for this other stuff too.

00:59:44.350 --> 00:59:46.440
So as they transition out of this state,

00:59:46.440 --> 00:59:47.770
I know that there's a
kind of a heightened,

00:59:47.770 --> 00:59:49.420
there's a so-called peak,

00:59:49.420 --> 00:59:50.710
- Yeah.
- where everything seems to be

00:59:50.710 --> 00:59:55.710
kind of cascading in at such
a level that the person just,

00:59:55.840 --> 00:59:57.800
they can't really turn
it off at that point.

00:59:57.800 --> 00:59:59.920
- Right.
- It would be challenging.

00:59:59.920 --> 01:00:04.920
And then they start to exit
the effects of the drug.

01:00:05.210 --> 01:00:07.250
Are those transition zones,

01:00:07.250 --> 01:00:08.240
are those valuable,

01:00:08.240 --> 01:00:10.830
much like is the
transition between a dream

01:00:10.830 --> 01:00:12.840
and the waking state valuable?

01:00:12.840 --> 01:00:16.560
Because you're in a sort of
mishmash of altered reality

01:00:16.560 --> 01:00:18.860
and new reality.
- Right.

01:00:18.860 --> 01:00:21.503
- What do you do to
guide people through the,

01:00:22.936 --> 01:00:23.970
out the tunnel,

01:00:23.970 --> 01:00:25.260
as they exit the tunnel?
- Yeah.

01:00:25.260 --> 01:00:26.370
And I have to say,

01:00:26.370 --> 01:00:30.240
this is where we need
more experimentation.

01:00:30.240 --> 01:00:32.450
Really, the clinical model goes back

01:00:32.450 --> 01:00:35.990
to literally the late 1950s,

01:00:35.990 --> 01:00:39.430
and there's been virtually
no experimentation on,

01:00:39.430 --> 01:00:42.050
let's say, randomized people to...

01:00:42.050 --> 01:00:43.070
We're going to talk more

01:00:43.070 --> 01:00:46.110
during the latter half of
the session, versus not.

01:00:46.110 --> 01:00:47.660
Versus we have them

01:00:47.660 --> 01:00:50.180
write an essay after
their session, versus not.

01:00:50.180 --> 01:00:52.377
Versus we have this amount of integration.

01:00:52.377 --> 01:00:53.540
[interposing voices]

01:00:53.540 --> 01:00:54.373
- In your studies,

01:00:54.373 --> 01:00:55.980
are they writing or talking

01:00:55.980 --> 01:00:56.830
as they're doing it?
- So-

01:00:56.830 --> 01:01:00.650
And it's called a very loosey
goosey term, integration,

01:01:00.650 --> 01:01:02.233
but for us means,

01:01:04.030 --> 01:01:05.930
as they're coming back
from the experience,

01:01:05.930 --> 01:01:08.110
so sort of five, six hours in,

01:01:08.110 --> 01:01:09.240
so this is the afternoon,

01:01:09.240 --> 01:01:10.680
they've been dosed around nine o'clock,

01:01:10.680 --> 01:01:13.180
so this is like four o'clock or so,

01:01:13.180 --> 01:01:15.430
just some initial, tell
us about the experience.

01:01:15.430 --> 01:01:16.263
Do you want to...

01:01:16.263 --> 01:01:17.350
Not unpacking it totally,

01:01:17.350 --> 01:01:18.350
but just kind of initially

01:01:18.350 --> 01:01:20.340
just have a little bit of
discussion before they go home.

01:01:20.340 --> 01:01:21.840
So there's a little bit of that.

01:01:21.840 --> 01:01:25.490
But then, that night, their
homework is to write something.

01:01:25.490 --> 01:01:27.750
So it could be a few bullet points.

01:01:27.750 --> 01:01:30.490
It could be 20 pages.

01:01:30.490 --> 01:01:34.020
And we get everything in that range.

01:01:34.020 --> 01:01:36.940
But try not to be self-critical.

01:01:36.940 --> 01:01:38.170
It's not graded.

01:01:38.170 --> 01:01:39.760
This is just to process,

01:01:39.760 --> 01:01:41.610
and for a point of
discussion the next day.

01:01:41.610 --> 01:01:42.470
So they write something,

01:01:42.470 --> 01:01:45.970
they come in the next
day for one to two hour,

01:01:45.970 --> 01:01:48.190
depending on the study,
"integration session",

01:01:48.190 --> 01:01:51.400
basically, let's discuss your experience.

01:01:51.400 --> 01:01:53.447
And depending on what study it's in,

01:01:53.447 --> 01:01:56.210
like what that mean for...

01:01:56.210 --> 01:01:57.200
You're dealing with cancer,

01:01:57.200 --> 01:01:59.503
what might that mean for your smoking,

01:02:00.510 --> 01:02:02.490
or becoming a non smoker?

01:02:02.490 --> 01:02:04.990
So you encourage them to
simply take it seriously.

01:02:04.990 --> 01:02:07.240
And I think this is, again, a sort of,

01:02:07.240 --> 01:02:09.870
one of the points that
could be the antithesis

01:02:09.870 --> 01:02:13.910
of what some just kind
of social users use.

01:02:13.910 --> 01:02:17.280
I mean, this was written
about by Huston Smith,

01:02:17.280 --> 01:02:18.350
the scholar of religion,

01:02:18.350 --> 01:02:20.810
in terms of these mystical experiences

01:02:20.810 --> 01:02:22.220
that can happen from psychedelics,

01:02:22.220 --> 01:02:24.000
and how a lot of times,

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:26.838
the attribution to a
drug effect is dismissed.

01:02:26.838 --> 01:02:31.838
Even if one has this sense of
being one with the universe,

01:02:32.170 --> 01:02:35.140
and it totally shakes
their soul, so to speak,

01:02:35.140 --> 01:02:36.740
but the next day, their friends are like,

01:02:36.740 --> 01:02:38.850
ah, dude, you were screwed up!

01:02:38.850 --> 01:02:40.160
Too much acid for you!

01:02:40.160 --> 01:02:40.993
Whoo!

01:02:40.993 --> 01:02:41.826
You know?

01:02:41.826 --> 01:02:43.850
Like, man, next time, you
needed to have a few more beers

01:02:43.850 --> 01:02:44.980
to bring that down.

01:02:44.980 --> 01:02:49.980
You know, like this sort
of social reinforcement

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:52.900
for dismissing the experience.

01:02:52.900 --> 01:02:55.300
Oh, god, you were talking
out of your head, man.

01:02:56.580 --> 01:02:58.240
Even if it's good natured,

01:02:58.240 --> 01:02:59.430
but it's this dismissal.

01:02:59.430 --> 01:03:00.680
It's not like...

01:03:01.650 --> 01:03:05.360
What you want to do is like,
tell me more about that.

01:03:05.360 --> 01:03:07.300
You know, you were crying at one point

01:03:07.300 --> 01:03:09.380
in talking about your mom.

01:03:09.380 --> 01:03:10.330
Let's talk about that.

01:03:10.330 --> 01:03:11.163
What was that like?

01:03:11.163 --> 01:03:12.134
Do you remember that?

01:03:12.134 --> 01:03:13.342
[interposing voices]

01:03:13.342 --> 01:03:14.780
- Are you doing that follow-up,

01:03:14.780 --> 01:03:16.680
or they're encouraged to
do that in their own life

01:03:16.680 --> 01:03:18.110
with the various people in their life?

01:03:18.110 --> 01:03:18.943
- Both.

01:03:18.943 --> 01:03:20.930
So we do that explicitly in the follow-up,

01:03:20.930 --> 01:03:22.830
where we have these discussions.

01:03:22.830 --> 01:03:26.580
Depending on what the situation is,

01:03:26.580 --> 01:03:29.830
you might encourage the
person to kind of follow-up.

01:03:29.830 --> 01:03:34.830
It's really, the basics of
it is, is supportive therapy.

01:03:35.960 --> 01:03:37.400
It's non-structured.

01:03:37.400 --> 01:03:40.170
It's use all the reflective listening,

01:03:40.170 --> 01:03:42.830
and the sort of the
humanistic psychology thing,

01:03:42.830 --> 01:03:45.260
unconditional positive
regard for the person.

01:03:45.260 --> 01:03:50.260
But I think, if someone feels inclined

01:03:50.840 --> 01:03:55.630
to apologize to their
sibling about some things,

01:03:57.060 --> 01:03:58.810
like, yeah, go ahead and call 'em up.

01:03:58.810 --> 01:04:01.200
With something big, like
a relationship change,

01:04:01.200 --> 01:04:04.210
I'd be like, sit on that two weeks.

01:04:04.210 --> 01:04:05.180
Don't make any big...

01:04:05.180 --> 01:04:06.580
Don't end any relationship.

01:04:06.580 --> 01:04:07.610
Don't quit your job.

01:04:07.610 --> 01:04:09.260
Don't make any big-
- Do you also tell them

01:04:09.260 --> 01:04:10.810
not to start any relationships?

01:04:13.860 --> 01:04:15.640
- I don't remember that ever coming up.

01:04:15.640 --> 01:04:17.270
- Interesting.
- But if it-

01:04:17.270 --> 01:04:18.190
- I'm not joking.

01:04:18.190 --> 01:04:19.270
I was just wondering, you know?

01:04:19.270 --> 01:04:20.103
- Yeah.
- But it makes sense

01:04:20.103 --> 01:04:21.030
why you would want-
- Like if they're dating,

01:04:21.030 --> 01:04:21.890
and they're thinking like,

01:04:21.890 --> 01:04:24.250
ah, it might be time to
take it to the next level.

01:04:24.250 --> 01:04:26.300
Should I ask this girl to marry me?

01:04:26.300 --> 01:04:29.299
If it did come up, I would say there too,

01:04:29.299 --> 01:04:30.207
why don't you sit on that

01:04:30.207 --> 01:04:31.040
a week or two?
- Yeah,

01:04:31.040 --> 01:04:32.470
don't get a puppy.
- And let your sober mind-

01:04:32.470 --> 01:04:33.460
- Don't get a puppy.

01:04:33.460 --> 01:04:34.900
Certainly, don't get four puppies

01:04:34.900 --> 01:04:36.230
until your...
[Dr. Matthew laughs]

