01:28:09.460 --> 01:28:11.660
of bringing the mind into these states?

01:28:11.660 --> 01:28:14.870
'Cause it sounds like a
very labile situation.

01:28:14.870 --> 01:28:16.740
So could we talk a little bit about that?

01:28:16.740 --> 01:28:18.950
And are there classes of
these different drugs,

01:28:18.950 --> 01:28:21.453
whether or not it be MDMA, LSD, or DMT,

01:28:22.430 --> 01:28:24.820
that you think are
particularly sharp blades,

01:28:24.820 --> 01:28:28.540
and therefore need to be
wielded particularly carefully?

01:28:28.540 --> 01:28:29.373
- Yeah.

01:28:29.373 --> 01:28:33.860
So these can be profoundly
de-stabilizing experiences,

01:28:35.320 --> 01:28:40.320
and ones that, ideally, are
had in a safe container,

01:28:43.370 --> 01:28:46.460
sort of where someone...

01:28:46.460 --> 01:28:47.890
What are the relevant dangers,

01:28:47.890 --> 01:28:49.750
and what can we do to mitigate those?

01:28:49.750 --> 01:28:52.883
So there's two biggies.

01:28:54.350 --> 01:28:55.900
One, and I've already mentioned,

01:28:55.900 --> 01:29:00.290
it's people with very
severe psychiatric illness.

01:29:00.290 --> 01:29:03.010
Not depression, not anxiety.

01:29:03.010 --> 01:29:06.700
I'm talking about psychotic
disorders like schizophrenia,

01:29:06.700 --> 01:29:10.003
or mania as part of bipolar disorder.

01:29:11.490 --> 01:29:13.170
And diagnostically, this has shifted.

01:29:13.170 --> 01:29:14.190
So it's a little hard to say

01:29:14.190 --> 01:29:15.860
how many people today with bipolar

01:29:15.860 --> 01:29:18.183
would have been labeled as
schizophrenia back in the '60s

01:29:18.183 --> 01:29:20.950
when some of this early research

01:29:20.950 --> 01:29:23.270
or just clinical observation was done.

01:29:23.270 --> 01:29:25.510
So it seems very clear

01:29:25.510 --> 01:29:28.260
that folks with a predisposition
or active disease,

01:29:28.260 --> 01:29:29.630
they could be destabilized.

01:29:29.630 --> 01:29:31.720
And so some of the cases that we know of,

01:29:31.720 --> 01:29:33.500
I always think of Syd Barrett,

01:29:33.500 --> 01:29:35.343
the first singer of Pink Floyd,

01:29:37.500 --> 01:29:38.960
seems pretty clear.

01:29:38.960 --> 01:29:39.793
Although, I think the family-
- I don't know

01:29:39.793 --> 01:29:40.650
what happened there.

01:29:40.650 --> 01:29:41.860
- So he-
- I should be...

01:29:41.860 --> 01:29:43.160
Sorry, Pink Floyd fans.

01:29:43.160 --> 01:29:43.993
I've never...

01:29:43.993 --> 01:29:45.340
The songs are just really long.

01:29:45.340 --> 01:29:46.950
- Yeah, you're more of a punk guy, right?

01:29:46.950 --> 01:29:47.846
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

01:29:47.846 --> 01:29:48.820
[both laughing]

01:29:48.820 --> 01:29:51.010
So I've got my foot in a lot of worlds,

01:29:51.010 --> 01:29:53.468
definitely in part in the Floyd world.

01:29:53.468 --> 01:29:58.003
But he basically went crazy early on.

01:29:58.960 --> 01:30:00.740
I don't think his family ever admitted it,

01:30:00.740 --> 01:30:04.683
but he developed
schizophrenia, classic pattern,

01:30:05.959 --> 01:30:07.459
and he was doing a lot of LSD.

01:30:08.610 --> 01:30:11.570
But like a lot of these cases,

01:30:11.570 --> 01:30:15.083
it looked like he was
showing all of the signs of,

01:30:17.080 --> 01:30:18.640
some hints of

01:30:21.200 --> 01:30:23.580
that he had that susceptibility before.

01:30:23.580 --> 01:30:26.490
And often, this is hard to
disentangle what causes what,

01:30:26.490 --> 01:30:30.560
because when do people, typically,
not always, but develop?

01:30:30.560 --> 01:30:32.430
When's the modal period for first break?

01:30:32.430 --> 01:30:33.950
It's adolescence, early adulthood.

01:30:33.950 --> 01:30:34.783
Yeah.

01:30:34.783 --> 01:30:37.218
And when do people start
playing with drugs?

01:30:37.218 --> 01:30:39.810
[laughs] Same exact time period,

01:30:39.810 --> 01:30:42.080
so it can be hard to disentangle.

01:30:42.080 --> 01:30:43.350
But it seems pretty clear.

01:30:43.350 --> 01:30:44.880
Now, I should also say,

01:30:44.880 --> 01:30:46.740
there are cases of
folks with schizophrenia

01:30:46.740 --> 01:30:48.750
that say psychedelics have helped them.

01:30:48.750 --> 01:30:50.685
There's anecdotes for everything, though.

01:30:50.685 --> 01:30:51.531
It's a big world.
- Do the people around

01:30:51.531 --> 01:30:52.844
those schizophrenics say it's helped them,

01:30:52.844 --> 01:30:53.677
or just-
- I don't know.

01:30:53.677 --> 01:30:54.840
- 'Cause when schizophrenics say things,

01:30:54.840 --> 01:30:56.340
you have to-
- You have to weight it.

01:30:56.340 --> 01:30:58.440
- I mean, with all due compassion

01:30:58.440 --> 01:30:59.700
and respect for schizophrenia,

01:30:59.700 --> 01:31:01.760
it's a disorder of thinking.

01:31:01.760 --> 01:31:03.740
So if they're saying, it helped them?

01:31:03.740 --> 01:31:04.930
- Yeah, can you trust them?

01:31:04.930 --> 01:31:05.763
Yeah.

01:31:05.763 --> 01:31:07.130
I wouldn't be surprised

01:31:07.130 --> 01:31:09.840
if there was some kernel
of truth in some cases,

01:31:09.840 --> 01:31:11.660
but they're just so...

01:31:11.660 --> 01:31:14.900
It seems very clear that
the other side is there too,

01:31:14.900 --> 01:31:16.160
and that if there ever is

01:31:16.160 --> 01:31:19.040
a therapeutic potential
there for those disorders,

01:31:19.040 --> 01:31:21.470
that that shouldn't be the
first thing on our list,

01:31:21.470 --> 01:31:23.180
and we need to learn a lot more,

01:31:23.180 --> 01:31:24.510
because of the level of risk,

01:31:24.510 --> 01:31:26.890
before we start doing research to see if

01:31:28.040 --> 01:31:30.110
psilocybin can help with schizophrenia.

01:31:30.110 --> 01:31:30.943
I don't think...
[Dr. Huberman mumbles]

01:31:30.943 --> 01:31:32.120
That may never be the case,

01:31:32.120 --> 01:31:33.430
but even if it is,

01:31:33.430 --> 01:31:35.210
you'd have to be even more cautious

01:31:35.210 --> 01:31:37.900
and figure some more things out first

01:31:37.900 --> 01:31:39.560
with some of these other disorders.

01:31:39.560 --> 01:31:41.090
- What about bipolar?
- 'Cause it seems-

01:31:41.090 --> 01:31:43.070
- Bipolar disorder, can it be exacerbated

01:31:43.070 --> 01:31:46.350
by these compounds?
- Yeah, and it's-

01:31:46.350 --> 01:31:50.310
It may be that, sort of the manifestation

01:31:50.310 --> 01:31:53.150
of people having prolonged
psychiatric issues

01:31:53.150 --> 01:31:56.580
after a psychedelic experience,

01:31:56.580 --> 01:31:58.850
as atypical as that is,

01:31:58.850 --> 01:32:01.360
when that happens, it may be that

01:32:01.360 --> 01:32:03.860
that might be more like a manic episode

01:32:03.860 --> 01:32:05.090
than a psychotic episode,

01:32:05.090 --> 01:32:06.743
and that can be a blurry line.

01:32:09.500 --> 01:32:10.950
The folklore is that,

01:32:10.950 --> 01:32:12.930
people go on a trip, and
they never come back.

01:32:12.930 --> 01:32:14.440
That's clearly not the case,

01:32:14.440 --> 01:32:17.497
because the drug is metabolized,
like for anyone else,

01:32:17.497 --> 01:32:19.114
and the next day,

01:32:19.114 --> 01:32:21.220
there's virtually nothing-
- But it reshapes circuitry.

01:32:21.220 --> 01:32:22.730
I mean-
- Right.

01:32:22.730 --> 01:32:24.260
And I really do think,

01:32:24.260 --> 01:32:28.140
much like the positive long-term effects

01:32:28.140 --> 01:32:32.363
that this class of problems is related to,

01:32:34.570 --> 01:32:38.130
the experience and the destabilization

01:32:38.130 --> 01:32:42.070
that can happen from that experience,

01:32:42.070 --> 01:32:44.730
if it's not in the right container.

01:32:44.730 --> 01:32:47.700
And again, these people
are susceptible to...

01:32:47.700 --> 01:32:50.830
You know, some people with
that psychotic predisposition,

01:32:50.830 --> 01:32:53.630
they lucky to be born to a great family,

01:32:53.630 --> 01:32:55.150
a stable environment.

01:32:55.150 --> 01:32:56.730
They maybe never have a full break,

01:32:56.730 --> 01:32:58.920
or the one that they
have is not nearly as bad

01:32:58.920 --> 01:33:02.940
as what someone who's homeless,

01:33:02.940 --> 01:33:06.100
and is coming from all kinds
of early childhood trauma.

01:33:06.100 --> 01:33:08.763
The disease is probably
going to be far worse.

01:33:10.720 --> 01:33:12.690
Having a psychedelic experience

01:33:12.690 --> 01:33:15.733
is like one of those
de-stabilizing experiences.

01:33:17.540 --> 01:33:20.530
Now, fortunately, it's really
easy to identify those people.

01:33:20.530 --> 01:33:23.530
And we even err on the
side of extreme caution

01:33:23.530 --> 01:33:25.240
by eliminating people with like, say,

01:33:25.240 --> 01:33:26.280
a first degree relative.

01:33:26.280 --> 01:33:28.650
In some studies, even a
second degree relative.

01:33:28.650 --> 01:33:29.940
Given the heritability,

01:33:29.940 --> 01:33:30.950
there's some increased chance

01:33:30.950 --> 01:33:33.060
- Sure.
- if your brother or your...

01:33:33.060 --> 01:33:33.893
Yeah.

01:33:35.340 --> 01:33:37.730
So in an abundance of caution,

01:33:37.730 --> 01:33:38.570
even eliminating that...

01:33:38.570 --> 01:33:43.190
I think, eventually, if it's
approved for use, FDA use,

01:33:43.190 --> 01:33:45.440
we could dial back on
that as we learn more.

01:33:45.440 --> 01:33:48.850
I think, it's, again, overly cautious,

01:33:48.850 --> 01:33:49.683
which is-
- But you're doing

01:33:49.683 --> 01:33:50.516
an early stage

01:33:50.516 --> 01:33:52.030
clinical trial, so.
- Yeah, it's the appropriate

01:33:52.030 --> 01:33:53.640
place to start at this point in time.

01:33:53.640 --> 01:33:56.280
But if you give a SCID,

01:33:56.280 --> 01:33:57.270
or another structured

01:33:57.270 --> 01:33:59.160
psychiatric interview with a clinician,

01:33:59.160 --> 01:34:00.890
sitting down with this
person for a few hours

01:34:00.890 --> 01:34:02.950
to delve into their history,

01:34:02.950 --> 01:34:05.200
like you could very reliably determine

01:34:05.200 --> 01:34:09.070
that this person has either
a psychotic disorder,

01:34:09.070 --> 01:34:12.123
or bipolar disorder, or
a strong predisposition.

01:34:13.430 --> 01:34:14.440
You can screen for that,

01:34:14.440 --> 01:34:15.910
and that's how you address that.

01:34:15.910 --> 01:34:18.840
The far more likely
danger is the bad trip.

01:34:18.840 --> 01:34:20.220
Anyone can have this.

01:34:20.220 --> 01:34:21.240
The most psychologically

01:34:21.240 --> 01:34:23.720
healthy person in the world, probably.

01:34:23.720 --> 01:34:25.100
You jack the dose high enough,

01:34:25.100 --> 01:34:29.220
and especially in a less
than an ideal environment,

01:34:29.220 --> 01:34:30.630
you can have a bad trip.

01:34:30.630 --> 01:34:33.480
You even get it in an
ideal environment like ours

01:34:33.480 --> 01:34:37.300
at a high dose of around 30
milligrams of psilocybin.

01:34:37.300 --> 01:34:40.020
After the best preparation we can provide,

01:34:40.020 --> 01:34:42.740
about a third of people
will say, essentially,

01:34:42.740 --> 01:34:44.920
at some point, they have a bad trip,

01:34:44.920 --> 01:34:45.753
and we'd-
- At some point

01:34:45.753 --> 01:34:47.370
within the entire journey.

01:34:47.370 --> 01:34:48.203
- Right.
- Yeah.

01:34:48.203 --> 01:34:49.036
- Now, they could have

01:34:49.036 --> 01:34:49.890
one of the most beautiful

01:34:49.890 --> 01:34:51.610
experiences of their life, sometimes,

01:34:51.610 --> 01:34:53.380
like a couple of minutes later.

01:34:53.380 --> 01:34:54.380
- Right.
- But at some point,

01:34:54.380 --> 01:34:57.130
they had a sense of strong anxiety, fear,

01:34:57.130 --> 01:35:01.410
losing their mind, feeling
trapped, something like that.

01:35:01.410 --> 01:35:04.640
Now, typically, when people have that,

01:35:04.640 --> 01:35:06.700
when they're just taken on their own,

01:35:06.700 --> 01:35:08.210
like a lot of things, they're fine.

01:35:08.210 --> 01:35:09.043
They get through it.

01:35:09.043 --> 01:35:11.150
They're more likely to be better off

01:35:11.150 --> 01:35:14.100
if they're not having to navigate
the streets of Manhattan.

01:35:15.340 --> 01:35:19.530
And if they're with other
people, with friends,

01:35:19.530 --> 01:35:21.000
better that those friends aren't

01:35:21.000 --> 01:35:23.030
also dealing with their
own psychedelic experience.

01:35:23.030 --> 01:35:25.329
But probably having
some friend of any type,

01:35:25.329 --> 01:35:27.270
[mumbles] is better than having nothing.

01:35:27.270 --> 01:35:30.340
So very dependent on context.

01:35:30.340 --> 01:35:32.280
And so the tough thing here

01:35:32.280 --> 01:35:35.803
that in conveying to the public is that,

01:35:36.820 --> 01:35:38.370
a lot of folks will say,

01:35:38.370 --> 01:35:41.070
man, I've taken psychedelics
hundreds of times,

01:35:41.070 --> 01:35:43.770
and this is like you're fear-mongering,

01:35:43.770 --> 01:35:46.540
and there's no,

01:35:46.540 --> 01:35:48.300
you're exaggerating the danger there.

01:35:48.300 --> 01:35:50.800
So I want to say, it is atypical,

01:35:50.800 --> 01:35:53.500
but sometimes, and I have a file folder

01:35:53.500 --> 01:35:57.720
that grows larger every
year of these cases,

01:35:57.720 --> 01:36:00.030
either in the medical
literature or from the news,

01:36:00.030 --> 01:36:02.170
of people that freak out on a psychedelic,

01:36:02.170 --> 01:36:04.740
and they get hurt or they die.

01:36:04.740 --> 01:36:07.210
They run into traffic.

01:36:07.210 --> 01:36:08.580
They fall from a height.

01:36:08.580 --> 01:36:10.070
Whether they thought they could fly,

01:36:10.070 --> 01:36:11.230
or whether they just fell,

01:36:11.230 --> 01:36:13.570
like you can do when you're drunk

01:36:13.570 --> 01:36:16.150
or you're intoxicated on any substance.

01:36:16.150 --> 01:36:18.710
Sometimes that's unclear.

01:36:18.710 --> 01:36:22.800
Or gosh, one of the
craziest cases was a kid,

01:36:22.800 --> 01:36:25.460
like an 18-year-old or so, in Oregon,

01:36:25.460 --> 01:36:27.420
several years back, that just...

01:36:27.420 --> 01:36:29.500
He even wrote about, I
want to take the biggest...

01:36:29.500 --> 01:36:30.333
He had done mushrooms before.

01:36:30.333 --> 01:36:32.410
I want to take a heroic dose.

01:36:32.410 --> 01:36:33.610
The biggest dose I've ever taken.

01:36:33.610 --> 01:36:35.680
He ended up just totally out of it.

01:36:35.680 --> 01:36:37.060
Ended up in a neighbor's house.

01:36:37.060 --> 01:36:38.560
He was just totally disoriented,

01:36:38.560 --> 01:36:39.393
disconnected from reality,

01:36:39.393 --> 01:36:41.650
and the cops and ended up killing him,

01:36:41.650 --> 01:36:42.730
and it was just tragic.

01:36:42.730 --> 01:36:45.330
Obviously, an overuse
of force in that case,

01:36:45.330 --> 01:36:46.830
'cause he was actually naked at the time.

01:36:46.830 --> 01:36:50.970
This naked like 120 pounds,
I think, as I recall, kid

01:36:50.970 --> 01:36:52.050
that ended up dying.

01:36:52.050 --> 01:36:53.240
But-
- Well, it's analogous

01:36:53.240 --> 01:36:56.320
to the reason I used the
examples of bodybuilding culture.

01:36:56.320 --> 01:36:57.430
I mean, people there have taken

01:36:57.430 --> 01:37:01.020
excessive amounts of anabolic
and diuretics, and died.

01:37:01.020 --> 01:37:02.500
Then the contortionist culture,

01:37:02.500 --> 01:37:03.333
people would put themselves

01:37:03.333 --> 01:37:05.590
in the little plexiglass boxes to do...

01:37:06.550 --> 01:37:08.210
At the extremes,

