And it's really interesting,

01:59:18.370 --> 01:59:23.310
because this FDA is very concerned
about pseudo-specificity.

01:59:23.310 --> 01:59:24.270
The idea that-
- Wait, could you define

01:59:24.270 --> 01:59:25.840
pseudo-specificity?
- You put out a drug,

01:59:25.840 --> 01:59:28.900
and say, oh, this is good
for men, but not women.

01:59:28.900 --> 01:59:31.680
This is good for black
folks, but not white folks.

01:59:31.680 --> 01:59:34.720
And now, sometimes, there's a
very good rationale for that,

01:59:34.720 --> 01:59:36.770
like when we're talking about hormones,

01:59:36.770 --> 01:59:38.033
and for a specific,

01:59:39.280 --> 01:59:40.337
for men versus women,

01:59:40.337 --> 01:59:43.723
and there's certain issues,

01:59:45.220 --> 01:59:46.170
certain disease states,

01:59:46.170 --> 01:59:47.830
like maybe sickle cell anemia,

01:59:47.830 --> 01:59:49.170
that's more relevant.
- Or Tay-Sachs,

01:59:49.170 --> 01:59:50.003
things like that.

01:59:50.003 --> 01:59:51.060
Sure.
- Yeah, exactly.

01:59:51.060 --> 01:59:52.790
But absent of something of that,

01:59:52.790 --> 01:59:54.740
they're very concerned about saying,

01:59:54.740 --> 01:59:56.760
oh, this is for this type of person,

01:59:56.760 --> 01:59:58.020
but not that type of person.

01:59:58.020 --> 01:59:59.630
So age is one of those things.

01:59:59.630 --> 02:00:01.910
And also, this recognition,

02:00:01.910 --> 02:00:04.100
much like the emphasis at NIH

02:00:05.550 --> 02:00:06.913
with rodent studies and human studies,

02:00:06.913 --> 02:00:09.870
that you can't just say,
"You're studying men".

02:00:09.870 --> 02:00:10.740
You need a rationale,

02:00:10.740 --> 02:00:11.750
if you're only [mumbles].

02:00:11.750 --> 02:00:13.880
- Yeah, to be clear to people, there's...

02:00:13.880 --> 02:00:15.380
It's a recent switch,

02:00:15.380 --> 02:00:19.850
but there's a stipulation in
every federally funded grant

02:00:19.850 --> 02:00:21.500
that both sexes,

02:00:21.500 --> 02:00:24.100
we don't refer to gender
in scientific studies,

02:00:24.100 --> 02:00:26.490
unless it's a study of gender, per se.

02:00:26.490 --> 02:00:28.910
We refer to sex, meaning biological sex,

02:00:28.910 --> 02:00:31.110
so that there's a stipulation,

02:00:31.110 --> 02:00:33.500
that in order to receive and
continue to receive funding,

02:00:33.500 --> 02:00:36.930
you have to do a studies on both males

02:00:36.930 --> 02:00:39.890
and females of that
species, including humans.

02:00:39.890 --> 02:00:42.070
- And at least, even if
you're not powered for it,

02:00:42.070 --> 02:00:44.690
at least looking at that
in exploratory analysis.

02:00:44.690 --> 02:00:48.310
Like as a grant reviewer,
I'm charged with looking at,

02:00:48.310 --> 02:00:50.770
did they address sex as a biologically

02:00:50.770 --> 02:00:52.180
relevant variable anyway?
- Right.

02:00:52.180 --> 02:00:53.063
Does the same-
- You just throw it in there-

02:00:53.063 --> 02:00:55.440
- Does the same drug
have different effects

02:00:55.440 --> 02:00:56.800
in males versus females?

02:00:56.800 --> 02:00:57.662
- Right.

02:00:57.662 --> 02:00:59.270
And you could at least look
at the trends, even again,

02:00:59.270 --> 02:01:00.740
if you're underpowered to look at those

02:01:00.740 --> 02:01:02.980
between subject-type effects.

02:01:02.980 --> 02:01:05.080
- Which is a great shift that didn't exist

02:01:06.080 --> 02:01:08.340
10 years ago.
- Right.

02:01:08.340 --> 02:01:10.530
- It sounds like we're
both on grants panels.

02:01:10.530 --> 02:01:11.920
As study section members,

02:01:11.920 --> 02:01:12.753
you didn't have to do that.

02:01:12.753 --> 02:01:14.600
Now, it's an important
biological variable.

02:01:14.600 --> 02:01:16.220
If you don't look at that,

02:01:16.220 --> 02:01:18.640
you, essentially, won't get your funding.

02:01:18.640 --> 02:01:20.000
- And age is a similar thing.

02:01:20.000 --> 02:01:21.210
So if the whole idea, like,

02:01:21.210 --> 02:01:23.040
man, if something could help kids,

02:01:23.040 --> 02:01:24.010
what's the rationale?

02:01:24.010 --> 02:01:24.990
So I think there's going to be...

02:01:24.990 --> 02:01:27.550
Now, obviously, you're going
to have in those studies

02:01:28.480 --> 02:01:31.050
at least just as much, probably more,

02:01:31.050 --> 02:01:34.770
it should be more, of
a cautionary approach.

02:01:34.770 --> 02:01:36.230
It's probably going to be...

02:01:37.120 --> 02:01:38.050
It would certainly,

02:01:38.050 --> 02:01:39.290
whatever disease states are looked at,

02:01:39.290 --> 02:01:41.360
are going to to have to be
probably treatment resistant,

02:01:41.360 --> 02:01:42.470
at least as a first step.

02:01:42.470 --> 02:01:43.303
You know, hey,

02:01:43.303 --> 02:01:44.136
the kids tried-
- Suicidal depression?

02:01:44.136 --> 02:01:44.969
- Yeah, yeah.

02:01:44.969 --> 02:01:46.710
And so all of that in the mix.

02:01:46.710 --> 02:01:50.640
But hey, if this stuff really helps people

02:01:51.520 --> 02:01:54.530
that are 25 or 30,

02:01:54.530 --> 02:01:57.847
what's the rationale that it
won't help a younger person?

02:01:57.847 --> 02:02:00.320
And there's these generic
kind of concerns about,

02:02:00.320 --> 02:02:02.750
the developing nervous system,

02:02:02.750 --> 02:02:05.340
is more susceptible to...

02:02:05.340 --> 02:02:06.520
I mean, it cuts both ways,

02:02:06.520 --> 02:02:07.557
'cause it's also more

02:02:07.557 --> 02:02:09.200
"plastic" generally
- Yeah.

02:02:09.200 --> 02:02:12.750
- and adaptable, maybe resilient
to injury in certain ways.

02:02:12.750 --> 02:02:15.170
But you hear the rhetoric about kids,

02:02:15.170 --> 02:02:16.330
their brains, and drugs,

02:02:16.330 --> 02:02:19.513
and it's like the developing
brain is a special concern.

02:02:20.780 --> 02:02:21.613
So yeah.

02:02:21.613 --> 02:02:23.830
But I think we're going to be
seeing research eventually.

02:02:23.830 --> 02:02:24.760
- That's interesting.

02:02:24.760 --> 02:02:29.760
I went to the high school
that is infamous, sadly,

02:02:30.040 --> 02:02:33.360
Gunn High School, for
having the highest degree,

02:02:33.360 --> 02:02:36.130
at least at one point,
of highest suicide rate.

02:02:36.130 --> 02:02:37.720
- Wow.

02:02:37.720 --> 02:02:39.070
- A very large number of suicides.

02:02:39.070 --> 02:02:41.480
This was written up in
the "Times" and elsewhere.

02:02:41.480 --> 02:02:44.060
- Is it very academically
successful school?

02:02:44.060 --> 02:02:45.240
- It's a very academically-
